PlanetHunter

NASA Space Apps Challenge Project

Machine Learning • Astronomy • Explainable AI • Exoplanet Detection

AI-powered exoplanet detection system developed during NASA Space Apps Challenge.

PlanetHunter analyzes astronomical datasets from NASA’s Kepler mission and identifies potential exoplanets using machine learning techniques. The project combines data preprocessing, feature engineering, explainable AI (XAI), and an interactive web interface to make exoplanet discovery more accessible and understandable.

Features

* Upload and analyze Kepler datasets in CSV format
* Machine learning based exoplanet detection
* Explainable AI (SHAP) interpretation for every prediction
* Planet-to-Earth comparison using physical characteristics
* Interactive web interface
* FastAPI backend and React frontend

How It Works

The system processes raw Kepler mission data and extracts features relevant to exoplanet detection.

Instead of relying solely on pre-classified labels, the model focuses on astrophysical indicators related to transit detection, including changes in stellar brightness and planetary characteristics.

The workflow:

1. Dataset upload
2. Data preprocessing and validation
3. Feature extraction
4. LightGBM prediction
5. SHAP explainability analysis
6. Planet similarity assessment
7. Result visualization

Technology Stack

Backend

* Python
* FastAPI
* Pandas
* NumPy
* LightGBM
* SHAP

Frontend

* React
* Next.js
* Tailwind CSS

Explainable AI

To improve transparency, PlanetHunter uses SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations).

For each detected exoplanet candidate, the system shows which features had the greatest influence on the model’s decision, helping users understand why an object was classified as a potential planet.

